Handling Null Values

There are several ways to handle null values in a dataset.

Fill in the missing values with the median value of each column.

diabetes_median <- diabetes %>%
mutate_all(~ ifelse(is.na(.), median(., na.rm = TRUE), .))

fill in the missing values with the mean value of each column

diabetes_mean <- diabetes %>%
mutate_all(~ ifelse(is.na(.), mean(., na.rm = TRUE), .))

fill in the missing values with the common value of each column

fill_mode <- function(x) {
  mode_val <- names(sort(table(x), decreasing = TRUE))[1] 
  x[is.na(x)] <- mode_val 
  return(x)
}

diabetes_mode <- diabetes %>%
mutate_all(fill_mode)

Handling Outliers

Z-score (z-score standardization) is a method for handling outliers. It is calculated using the following formula:

\[ Z = \frac{{X - \bar{X}}}{{\sigma}} \]

where:

  • \(X\) is the specific value.

  • \(\bar{X}\) is the mean of the variable.

  • \(\sigma\) is the standard deviation of the variable.

This method helps standardize the data and identify values that deviate significantly from the mean.

diabetes_z <- (diabetes - colMeans(diabetes)) / apply(diabetes, 2, sd)
head(diabetes_z)

\[ \text{Scaled Value} = \frac{{X - \text{min}(X)}}{{\text{max}(X) - \text{min}(X)}} \]

min_max_scaler <- function(x) {
  return ((x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x)))
}

diabetes_scale <- as.data.frame(lapply(diabetes_f, min_max_scaler))

Hm kim tra m hnh

# Dng ma trn nhm ln
accuracy <- function() {
  predictions <- predict(model, newdata = dfTest, type = "class")
  
  # So snh gia gi tr d on v gi tr thc t
  confusion_matrix <- table(predictions, dfTest$Outcome)
  print(confusion_matrix)
  
  # Tnh ton  chnh xc t ma trn nhm ln
  accuracy <- sum(diag(confusion_matrix)) / sum(confusion_matrix)
  return (accuracy)
}

Tnh entropy cho cc thuc tnh

# Tnh entropy cho tng ct trong dfTrain
# Hm tnh entropy
calculate_entropy <- function(attribute_vector) {
  total_count <- length(attribute_vector)
  values <- table(attribute_vector)
  probabilities <- values / total_count
  entropy <- -sum(probabilities * log2(probabilities))
  return(entropy)
}

calculate_entropy_for_columns <- function(data) {
  entropy_values <- numeric()
  for (col in names(data)) {
    entropy <- calculate_entropy(data[[col]])
    entropy_values <- c(entropy_values, entropy)
  }
  names(entropy_values) <- names(data)
  return(entropy_values)
}

# Tnh entropy cho cc ct trong dfTrain
entropy_values <- calculate_entropy_for_columns(dfTrain)

Classifying the categories of Mass (BMI) using Random Forest model

The World Health Organization (WHO) classifies adults based on the following BMI ranges:

  • Underweight: < 18.5 kg/m^2

  • Normal weight: 18.5 - 24.9 kg/m^2

  • Overweight: 25.0 - 29.9 kg/m^2

  • Obese: 30.0 kg/m^2

library(ggplot2)

Tm s cy trong rng m hnh cho kt qu tt nht vi mtry = 3

# Lp li qu trnh hun luyn v nh gi trn cc gi tr khc nhau ca ntree
error_out_of_bag <- c()

for (ntree in 1:100) {
    # Hun luyn m hnh
    model <- randomForest(BMI_Category ~ . -Age -Pregnancies, data = train, ntree = ntree, mtry=3)

    # Tnh li ra ngoi ti
    error_out_of_bag[ntree] <- mean(predict(model, train) != train$BMI_Category)
}

# V ng cong li
plot(error_out_of_bag, type = "l", col = "red", ylab = "OOB error", xlab="S cy trong rng")

Cch 1: One-Sample T-test

gi thuyt BMI (Ch s khi c th) trung bnh 31 d mc bnh tiu ng

library(knitr)
# V biu  histogram
ggplot(diabetes_filter, aes(x = BMI)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 2, fill = "lightblue", color = "black") + 
  labs(x = "BMI", title = "Histogram of BMI") + theme_minimal() 

# summary statistics
kable(summary(select(diabetes_filter, BMI)), format = "markdown")
BMI
Min. : 0.00
1st Qu.:27.30
Median :32.00
Mean :31.96
3rd Qu.:36.52
Max. :67.10

###gi thuyt BMI trung bnh mc bnh tiu ng l 31

\[ H_0: bmi = 31 \] \[ H_a: bmi \neq 31 \]

t.test(diabetes_filter$BMI, mu=31)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  diabetes_filter$BMI
## t = 3.3476, df = 759, p-value = 0.0008554
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 31
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  31.39687 32.52234
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  31.95961

Kt lun v gii thch

  • T u ra v t p.value chng ta thy rng
  • p-value nh mc ngha 5%.
  • Ging nh bt k bi kim tra thng k no khc , nu p-value nh hn mc ngha th c th bc b gi thuyt. > Da vo kt qu kim nh t-test, c th kt lun rng gi tr trung bnh thc s ca ct BMI khng bng 31, v c lng trung bnh ca mu c th nm trong khong t 31.43410 n 32.55106 vi mc tin cy 95%.

-

Cch 2: Independent Samples T-test

chng minh phn trm m trong c th cng nh hng n vic c mc bnh hay khng

gi thuyt lng m trong c th (BMI) khng nh hng n vic c bnh hay khng**

# V biu  histogram
ggplot(diabetes_filter, aes(x = BMI_Category)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "count") + 
  labs(title = "Distribution of BMI Categories", x = "BMI Category", y = "Count") + 
  theme_bw()

###gi thuyt t l BMI ca ngi bnh v khng bnh l nh nhau \[ H_0: bmi_0 = bmi_1 \] \[ H_a: bmi_0 \neq bmi_1 \]

#ly ra nhng ngi bnh v khng bnh c ch s BMI_Category >= 3
sick <- num_diabetes[num_diabetes$Outcome==1 & num_diabetes$BMI_Category >= 3,10]
normal <- num_diabetes[num_diabetes$Outcome==0 & num_diabetes$BMI_Category >= 3,10]

t.test(normal,sick,var.equal=FALSE)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  normal and sick
## t = -6.01, df = 628.24, p-value = 3.145e-09
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.2659647 -0.1349627
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  3.642674  3.843137

Kt lun v gii thch

  • T u ra v t p.value chng ta thy rng
  • p-value nh hn mc ngha 5%.
  • Ging nh bt k bi kim tra thng k no khc , nu p-value nh hn mc ngha th c th bc b gi thuyt. > Da vo kt qu kim nh t-test, c th kt lun rng lng m trong c th c nh hng n vic ngi c bnh tiu ng .

chng minh tui cng nh hng n vic ngi c b bnh tiu ng hay khng.
